In Class Work

NMDS

similar to PCA

  • get distance matrix
  • use different distance/dissimilarity methods
  • algo. generates new ordination (order for values)
  • compares order to initial distance matrix. Calculate goodness of fit (called stress)
  • finds minimum stress value. Plots how samples are arranged in 2-D.

Bray Curtis

  • doesn’t vary when units change
  • unaffected by addition or removal of species not found in a pair of communities. (if 2 sites share a set of species, they should be similar)
  • unaffected by adding new communities/sites
  • Can show difference in abundance, ie. if one site is far more abundance than another even though the two sites share the same number of species.
  • value of 1 = sites have nothing in common
  • value of 0 = sites are identical
veg = read.csv("bryceveg.txt", header=TRUE, sep=' ', row.names=1)
sites = read.csv("brycesite.txt", header=TRUE, sep=' ', row.names=1)

meta-MDS

slightly fancier than normal NMDS, does refitting for us automatically

PCA gives us one principal componenet per column in dataset, MDS gives us k components (depending on what k we specify)

# k=2 means do this in 2 dimensions
bc.nmds = metaMDS(comm = veg, distance = "bray", k = 2, trace = 0)

bc.nmds
## 
## Call:
## metaMDS(comm = veg, distance = "bray", k = 2, trace = 0) 
## 
## global Multidimensional Scaling using monoMDS
## 
## Data:     veg 
## Distance: bray 
## 
## Dimensions: 2 
## Stress:     0.1405379 
## Stress type 1, weak ties
## Best solution was repeated 1 time in 20 tries
## The best solution was from try 10 (random start)
## Scaling: centring, PC rotation, halfchange scaling 
## Species: expanded scores based on 'veg'

stress value is ~0.14. General rule of thumb is that below 0.2, below 0.1 is very good, 0 is best.

pl = ordiplot(
  bc.nmds, 
  type='none', 
  main=paste0( # plot title
    'Stress = ', 
    round(bc.nmds$stress,dig=3)
    )
  )

points(pl, what='sites', col="black", pch=4) # add points for the sites

points(pl, what='species', col='tomato', pch=20) # add points for the species

legend( # add legend at bottom
  'bottomright', 
  legend=c('Sites', 'Species'), 
  col=c('black', 'tomato'), 
  pch=c(4,20)
  )

Stress

Stress is the goodness of fit measurement. A stress of 0.2 means roughly 80% of the variation in the original distance matrix can be explained by the 2 MDS components.

Ordination Plots

pl = ordiplot(
  bc.nmds, 
  type='none', 
  main=paste0( # plot title
    'Stress = ', 
    round(bc.nmds$stress,dig=3)
    )
  )

# add points for sites where berries present
points(pl, veg$berrep>0, what='sites', col="tomato", pch=20)

# add points for sites where berries absent
points(pl, veg$berrep == 0, what='sites', col='black', pch=20)

legend( # add legend at bottom
  'bottomright', 
  legend=c('Berries present', 'Berries absent'), 
  col=c('tomato', 'black'), 
  pch=c(20,20),
  title=expression(italic(Berries ~ repens))
  )

There’s no units on an NMDS plot, because we converted to a rank-order. Typically there’s not even ticks on an axis when publishing the values.

Standardization and transformation

  • metaNMDS applies a default transformation
  • some common transformations:
    1. sq root transformation
    2. 4th root (double sq root)
    3. log-transform
    4. Wisconsin

Homework

instructions

  • Run a NMDS on the bird data (macnally_full2.csv, leave out columns 1&2, SITE + HABITAT), using Bray-Curtis as the distance metric with the vegan metaMDS function

  • Generate a NMDS ordination plot showing the sites only (no species arrows), and draw ellipsoid hulls around each of the 6 habitat types to show how habitat maps onto the ordination.

    • Color the site points by HABITAT type (column 2 of data frame)

    • Use the ordiellipse() function, and the groups argument should be defined using the HABITAT data in column 2 of the data frame

    • Include a legend in the plot to show which point color maps to which habitat type

ordination plot with just sites

bird.plot = ordiplot(
  bird.nmds, 
  type='none', 
  main=paste0( # plot title
    'Stress = ', 
    round(bird.nmds$stress,dig=4) # add stress label to title
    ),
  xaxt='none', # remove tick marks from NMDS plots 
  yaxt='none'
  ) 

# add data points
points(
  bird.plot, 
  what='sites', 
  col=as.numeric(bird$HABITAT), # color by habitat
  pch=as.numeric(bird$HABITAT) # shape by habitat
  )

legend( # add legend at bottom left
  'bottomleft', 
  legend=levels(bird$HABITAT),
  col=1:6, # make the colors match the points
  pch=1:6, # make the shapes match
  cex=0.8,
  title="Habitat"
  )

ordiellipse(
  bird.nmds, 
  kind='ehull', # how to include points, this means all (?)
  draw="polygon", 
  col=1:6,
  alpha=0.2,
  groups=bird$HABITAT, 
  label=F
  )

Question: Based on your plot, describe which (if any) of the habitats differ in community composition

Answer: Two of the habitats are clearly different from the others in the NMDS ordination plot: Box-Ironbank and Red River Gum. These points do not overlap at all with any other habitat. The remaining habitats all overlap the mixed group.
